Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists from the University of California at Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among the stars related, that is, arose from one cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and briefly you can find them on the university website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, preceding the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the stars-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster can lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulations carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to simulate two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
Within a few million years, this object under the influence of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added label paints to the initial gas flows and found that due to rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud, a high degree of chemical homogeneity is achieved.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to look for relatives stars in chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
