Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that protects trade union organization as a civil law.
“Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs,” says Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chairs the Progressive Faction Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to introduce the Workers’ Empowerment Act along with Civil Rights Movement symbol John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal opportunities to discriminate against trade union organizations as other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of trade union opponents.
Amending the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to allow workers facing discrimination for participating in trade union organizations to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive damages and punitive payments - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to sort out what Allison, Lewis, and the co-authors of the bill suggest is to recall a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have been subjected to in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution drafted to ensure that Hideki Tojo's militarized autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions played a role in shaping a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, and to negotiate, and to act collectively is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will have no legal effect; measures aimed at this purpose will be recognized as illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights to be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions — and to have that union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as well.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights — and the expansion of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against trade union organization — is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge temporarily blocks legislation that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the US, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of the Louisiana law, which his supporters say he is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginadle in June and was due to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients in a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
“Claims will be allowed to work legally, continuing actions to obtain authority,” wrote in his decision, Judge John deGravels.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month, at which the judge will make a more permanent decision on this law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a string of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to gain hospital powers.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women are protected from an insidious law that seeks to deny them health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who did not act as plaintiffs in the case, and also applied for admission powers.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts have recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in that state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admissions laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one physician who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admissions authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state are forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish abortion doctors while their applications for admission authority await a decision.
What will result from the introduction of quotas for domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of product in the range of retail chains should be Russian-made, said the Deputy of the state Duma from the faction “Fair Russia” Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at the introduction of protective measures against domestic producers, the newspaper “Izvestia”.
The document will still be detailed to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. For the remaining groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers, "Nilov told the publication.
Together with the amendments to the article "On the basis of state regulation of trade activities in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced VAT rate of 10% for the sale of products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in retail chains is included in the package of incentive measures for Russian manufacturers.
There will be several times more domestic goods on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company "Nalogovik", a member of the independent expert center "Public Duma" Sergei Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
There will be farmers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that the profit will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate to retailers their terms and prices, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian producers will be able to increase the volume of their activities and sales, which will lead to the payment of higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will be mastered faster, and a contribution to GDP growth will be made.
Russia’s dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, though not immediately,” the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break into the shelves of local stores due to the high competition from foreign analogues.
Now that the embargo has been imposed, this niche has been liberated and it is possible to breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary checks on the Russian market will receive food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia.
In other words, now is the moment of calm, when the former players have already left, and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as an increase in prices for finished products, ”said Tamara Kasyanova, First Vice President of the All-Russian Public Organization “Russian Club of Financial Directors”.
Definitely, the idea to sell at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow to consolidate the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper due to subsidies from another state.
In other words, the fight for the buyer will unfold between companies operating under the same laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian producers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots not in all articles.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to “reach” the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that low-quality goods will arrive on the shelves.
Perhaps, under the guise of products produced in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied,” the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in this scenario, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not exclude that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to raise prices for the second, as for a scarce product.
The idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, was again discussed by economists in February this year due to the continuous devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products becomes even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers in the formation of orders to suppliers to take into account with domestic manufacturers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently along the path of import substitution, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," says deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be especially effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to fully cover the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, meat production can also get a powerful impetus.
As you know, the largest share of imports remains for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% is still on Russian products,” Kasyanova says.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can speed up this process.
However, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, since this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that full import substitution will not happen, but significant steps will be taken in this direction.
In addition, it is not enough to establish quotas, it is also necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees and will provide,” the expert states.
Delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who say goodbye in rural Australia face a higher risk of death from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
Researchers analyzed disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 per cent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research reported that those living in regions and remote areas of the state are 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
NEXT RESEARCH: New drugs may slow lung cancer and ovarian cancer
The researchers tracked the women’s medical path over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that a woman’s age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those with advanced cancer at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside of cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of on-site services that will allow professionals to treat women closer to home and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from their home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Neeve, was told that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
