Inflation is out of vacation.
Will the Russians feel a sharp rise in prices
As a result of cross-sanctions of the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the forecasts of the authorities, analysts of VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflation shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year and even less - 6.5%.
However, according to the newspaper “Kommersant”, this week the MAYOR should make “small, but fundamental” adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency can lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zero growth in household income.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation are valid for a year - until August 2015.
How could such high inflation be expected in such a situation?
The current situation suggests a one-time shock, but the downward trend in inflation will not change, ”the source of the newspaper in the Ministry of Finance said.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the financial and economic bloc of the government regarding inflation and predict an increase in prices in 2014 at the level of 8%.
The main effect of product bans will come along with the possible introduction of a sales tax (NST) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
Inflationary peak of 9% will occur in February, after which the annual growth rate of prices will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after the Russian Federation imposed “accurate sanctions”.
AIF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, Head of AForex FC Analytical Department:
Price growth is already observed for the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially significant products began to rise in price, the government was forced to launch measures of systematic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent the risks of unjustified price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators so that authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiates price increases.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the enormous rate of capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, as well as an embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures were to remain under control, the cost of a basket of the minimum set of products would not jump 12% in a single quarter.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a supply shock in the domestic market and led to a completely logical increase in the final value.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the mechanism of import substitution, as well as to increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry risks of growth of the inflation component.
If we add to this the fiscal reasons related to the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the deteriorating prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvaev, Director of the analytical department of Alpari
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in zero it was also above the current level, another thing is that then it was compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think by the end of the year, inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, managing the assets of the Maguta Foundation
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia has so far been successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector, this can lead to certain difficulties and increase the inflation expectations of the population, which are usually manifested in purchases of cash currency in order to protect their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and state regulation.
But the rise in prices begins traditionally after the summer lull and, perhaps, this autumn will become more tangible.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to stand, since the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
Gardening centers are saddened by the decline in the number of homeowners
Such a drop, driven by an exceptional decline in the number of homeowners under 35, could cause horticultural centers to start losing tens of millions of pounds a year as today’s young consumers reach the “basic horticultural age,” according to an HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to this report, people who rent a house spend an average of 55 percent of the amount that owners of their own homes spend on gardening.
It mentions an increase in the number of people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting yards in front of the house for parking, and the shrinking size of the garden as other factors posing a threat to the industry, whose annual sales are estimated to be 5 billion euros.
In Greater London, where the number of homeowners has fallen from 61 per cent to 43 per cent in six years, the UK has the lowest spending rate on horticultural goods per household.
HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society reported that renting a home and not having space for a garden does not mean that people cannot grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief horticultural adviser at RHS, said: “Plant growing in containers, for example, is especially popular with tenants who can carry plants with them when they move.
The HTA report defined the period between 1997 and 2005 as the "golden age" of horticultural retailing as a result of the increase in homeownership and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year due to better weather after unfavorable conditions in March and April last year.
