China's biggest companies join forces against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China’s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, instant messenger, etc.) and Baidu (the largest Chinese search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left behind even its American rivals - eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
Union of Largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($ 814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% by each of the Internet companies, the Wanda Group said.
The company is planned to be registered in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with a number of users of about 438 million people), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial real estate properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $ 8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and theme park in Qindao (a city in eastern China on the shores of the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $ 960 million.
Wanda also owns AMC Entertainment Holdings, making it the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, the development of which will be carried out by the newly created competitor Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company, thanks to the merger, Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new platform should become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, notes Dong Tse.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce,” said Wang Jianlin, Wanda’s chief executive.
“There is no real O2O site in China right now, and in this situation, everyone’s chances are about equal,” he said.
China’s e-commerce market is the world’s largest, and McKinsey & Co. estimates that its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, according to Bloomberg official statistics: this is more than the population of any country in the world, except India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015 this number could grow to 850 million people.
Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huateng was China’s richest man until recently, but according to the Bloomberg Millionaires Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion comes from his share in Alibaba.
Baidu CEO Robin Li now ranks third among China’s richest people, while Wang Jianlin of Wanda ranks fourth.
“Behind this battle is very interesting to watch: the three richest people join forces to challenge the even richer,” Cao Lei, director of China’s Hangzhou e-commerce research center, told Bloomberg.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after the creation: “Rome can not be built in one day.”
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only for new companies, but also for the well-deserved leaders of the global e-commerce, is evidenced by the report on Alibaba’s financial performance for the last quarter published on the eve.
Alibaba is often described as a cross between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba’s net profit for the period is almost two times higher than the same sum of competitors - it grew almost three times year-on-year and amounted to $ 1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has huge potential for money generation, largely due to its mobile apps,” said a report by an analyst at Hong Kong’s Arete Research Service.
According to Alibaba’s updated prospectus on the US Securities and Exchange Commission website, the number of active mobile users of the company’s services in July amounted to 188 million, which significantly exceeds the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions over the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba will have to name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company can be estimated at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba’s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) may take place on September 16.
Road-show of the company, preceding this event, will start on September 3.
Alibaba’s IPO is expected to be a record in the history of the NYSE and will allow the company to raise about $ 20 billion.
Until now, the record for the volume of funds raised on US exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 held an initial placement of its shares, earning $ 17.9 billion on this.
