The first day of spring was marked by wet and windy conditions that affected flights at Adelaide Airport
Spring has prepared a cold surprise in southern South Australia, bringing torrential rains and strong winds that have affected flights at Adelaide Airport.
Another 5 mm of rain fell on the city in the evening at 9 pm, following the 6.6 mm that fell over the night of Sunday.
The last rain was preceded by a couple of short showers with gusty winds, including a thunderstorm that began shortly before 8 pm and poured out almost 4 mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter gave out an early portion of spring last week, temperatures fell again on Monday to a high of just 15.8C in the city.
The squalid conditions are believed to have been one of the reasons for the delay in the landing of the Virgin Airlines flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was scheduled to land just after 7:30 p.m., but fell into a wind shear zone — a sudden change in speed or wind direction over a short distance — and was forced to gain altitude.
Wind gusts reached 50 km/h on the ground at Adelaide Airport at this time.
Flight data showed that the plane had to gain altitude during the second landing, and the plane eventually landed around 8:40 p.m.
