Calculation of the cost of construction projects in the Russian Federation will occur in a new way
Issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks, the Federal Antimonopoly Service takes on special control.
The FAS has created an expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector.
At its meeting, the head of the Department of control of housing and communal services, construction and natural resources of the FAS Vadim Solovyov said that “today’s calculation of the estimates of construction sites is completely incomprehensible.”
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to an unreasonable construction price, according to the FAS.
And they propose to determine the cost of construction of state-owned facilities at the design stage on the basis of market prices of design solutions instead of the estimated norms used today and unit prices for technological operations.
These proposals are included in the roadmap and are now under consideration in the Ministry of Construction.
"The replacement of traditional estimate documentation in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry," Vadim Solovyov explained to RGB.
After all, now every bolt and nut is calculated in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury “whole tractors” in the documentation.
In Minstroy, FAS agrees.
"The first developments in the transition to the calculation of the cost of structural elements are already there: methods have been developed for calculating prices for design solutions, drawing up estimates for these indicators," said Elena Zhukova, head of the Department of Urban Planning and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction.
The field of road construction was chosen as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko told "RGB", the estimated standards have long been outdated, but the business has not yet been offered another mechanism.
“As for the proposed calculations for structural elements, in practice this is difficult to implement, since completely different technologies are often used in the construction of buildings,” he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely due to the state order.
According to the Chairman of the Board of the NP "Expert community of professionals of state order" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, deputy director for engineering at Rosatom’s industry capital construction center, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to the contract portfolio, and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors in this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is maximally protected from someone’s managerial influence.
At the expert council, it was proposed to form a state order system in such a way that the same contractor is not entitled to receive more than one contract worth more than 1 billion rubles. or several contracts worth more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case, it will be necessary to give the customer the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the staff of the customer and budget expenditures for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer’s specialists will have to have the knowledge to assess the quality of work performed by contractors, as well as their safety.
Often, with this breakdown, it will be necessary to determine who will be responsible for the security of the facility as a whole.
In addition, this approach may lead to the outflow of highly qualified participants in public procurement due to a lack of interest in obtaining a state order for an incomplete volume of work and a small amount of the contract.
Deputy head of the expert and consulting center of the Institute of procurement Alexander Evstashenkov believes that now the procedure of the state order has turned into a business game for the attentiveness of the contractor.
And gave the following example: "the participant when filling out the application should indicate "specific indicators" without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "should be", "from", "more", "less", "analogue", "or", "type", "similar", "not lower", "lower", "higher", "may", "may", "earlier", "not earlier", "not higher", "not allowed".
Thus, customers often abuse their right to establish requirements for the content of the application submitted by contractors.
Another problem 44-FZ, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the “paper” proposal of the participant at the stage of application.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to assess only the qualifications of the contractor, but not the quality of work, the implementation of which has not even begun, the expert believes.
The quality of the work can be assessed only when they are accepted.
At the expert council, it was also proposed to move the marginal income from the upper to the lower echelon, so that intermediate contractors disappear.
Chairman of the Expert Council, State Secretary, Deputy Head of the FAS Andrey Tsarikovsky believes that this is not worth it, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise it will turn out, as in the famous reprise of Arkady Raikin’s “Atelier”: “Do you have a claim to the buttons?”
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went to school again on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and rain bombs rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory recovered from fighting.
The start of school has brought joy and excitement to the missile-affected settlements of southern Israel, but traces of fighting have remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the Pashos kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed traces of fragments from the walls and children's slides before the arrival of students.
“We’re a little scared, but happy to look to the future,” said Ronit Barth, a Kibbutz resident and English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was “a little strange” to start going to school again.
“It was a difficult time and we didn’t leave our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is located near the Gaza border, to express his support.
Before the cease-fire halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad had not taken to the streets or fled their homes, fleeing to safer areas further from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a piece of Palestinian landmine, doubt that they should go back.
The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families have not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the Gaza border that has tried hard from Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, "We will do our best to give you knowledge and ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately ended the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of proximity talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to Palestinian and UN estimates.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gazan militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
The Israeli attacks have damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools, which have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials delayed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope that the school will open soon so that we can complete our education like children around the world and Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza’s schools.
According to a popular criterion, real estate prices showed the largest winter growth in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic index for home prices in the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
This increase led to a cumulative increase for June, July and August of 4.2 percent, the largest increase in the winter months since 2007.
Annual price growth was 10.9 percent, more than double the 12 months to August 2013, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
RP Data research director Tim Lawless said Sydney and Melbourne have a two-tier market.
RP Data figures show that in Sydney, house prices have risen by 16.1 percent over the past year, while in Melbourne - by 11.7 percent.
The next most powerful markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices averaged between five and six percent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which was hit by government spending cuts, where prices rose just 1.4 percent year-on-year.
Mr Lawless said that now that the spring has begun, there will be an increase in the number of properties for sale over the next few months, which will be a "real test" for the market.
“Given the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sales and the current low-interest-rate environment, it is likely that home values will rise further over the next three months,” he said.
How people live in the oldest house of Ufa
In the former house of gold miners and miners Evdokima and his son Ivan Demidov on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 (former Bolshaya Kazanskaya) 18 apartments.
The house of the XVIII century since the time of construction has not changed much, except for dilapidation.
Outsiders go here as a tour, and the residents suffer more than rejoice, from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is almost 300 years old.
An old courtyard, always an open door, a creaking staircase.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls have cracked, and in the lumens of the plaster, in some places, the street is visible.
Everything seems to be based on an honest word.
And the locals say, "You don't think that's true."
To live in a wooden house of the XVIII century is very difficult, - says Tatiana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment number 3.
The object is on the state guard, but the money for its maintenance has not been allocated for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits, which the authorities simply forgot about.
The last repair was 40 years ago.
The walls still hold, but the foundation is rotten.
Many residents still go to the toilet on the street, and wash once a week in a public bath.
How can you be happy in such conditions?
The road passes directly under the windows, there is not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls back the curtain.
Now you can see what was only heard before: a stream of cars is rushing under the windows.
You see, the glass rattles constantly, we can not open the windows, and we are used to the noise.
People get used to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are gold.
We have two rooms, three of us with our son.
And for other families, the conditions are much worse, on the second floor in general, the ceilings are slightly more than one and a half meters high.
For contrast, Tatiana offers to visit a neighbor from apartment No. 6 Lyudmila Starostina.
A pleasant hospitable woman from the threshold offers a cup of coffee and says with a sad smile:
We have a one-bedroom apartment, 14.5 m2 for four people, and we live: my husband and daughter and granddaughter.
I have been here since birth, there has never been another living space, - Lyudmila wraps her eyes around the room: entresoli, two sofas with the letter "g"; on one of them there is a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very closely and not much different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical".
But from the ceiling regularly flows: the water system is not suitable anywhere.
Lyudmila speaks of her apartment as ordinary and amazing at the same time, like an Italian woman whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it reduces to one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The water supply was carried out about 40 years ago during the last repair.
Then they made us a small kitchen in a corner and a toilet from the former closet.
We live exactly where Demidov and his family lived, there were servants on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
In the real estate center of Ufa, they say, privatization does not matter.
We still get only a one-room apartment, we can not claim more.
Already four months ago, they promised to resettle us, but the promises did not go further.
I’m not used to complaining and I won’t.
In this apartment (room!) lived a whole dynasty: my grandmother and grandfather, my mother and father, my husband and my daughter with my granddaughter.
Everything happened during that time.
For example, big rats ran around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they are meter thick!
They say that the solution was mixed with eggs, so it lasts so long.
The house is well built, thank you Demidov!
Maybe that’s why no one has been killed by a collapsed ceiling or pile.
Only the building is still slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house rot, the floors repeatedly failed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground, like a well.
They say, and so it is - under our room a secret loophole and a passage to the White River, which was specially made by the old believers who once lived here, so that you could hide from danger, in case of what.
They were being chased.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how a historian came to them, begged them to let him start excavations in the apartment.
And then he persuaded them to give the living space in exchange for his one-man apartment on October Avenue.
Lyudmila refused the historian:
Where are we four in one?
And here, at least a tiny hope is that they will give housing more spacious.
If we agreed to the exchange, we would not have won anything.
The old man’s family won nothing.
The biggest dream of Lyudmila to be resettled, and the daughter with a 16-year-old granddaughter was given a separate room.
That is, two families allocated a two-room apartment instead of the most majestic ruins in which two generations now live.
Cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakov from apartments No. 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There in two small rooms with a total area of 23 m2, called apartments, lives her large family.
There are seven of us, two children.
You can see for yourself what the conditions are.
Plaster falls off in pieces, like window frames, in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms through holes.
The water in the faucet is only cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house of Ufa, you can see that the most fortunate couple Lavrentiev from apartment number 4.
They occupy the most spacious rooms of the first floor.
You're right, there's plenty of room.
The room is 75 squares, three people are registered.
We live in those rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high, spacious.
One bad thing - everything around cracks at the seams, falls apart, collapses.
The neighbors have already told us!
Most of the suffering we have with the floors: wooden boards rotted, the ground literally went from under our feet.
I've put up props, wedges; there's nothing in the hall yet, and in the other room we walk like swings, so shaky everything.
About the house of the merchant Evdokima Demidov Alexander Dmitrievich can tell better than any guide.
He treats the goldsmith like a native, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kaginsky and Uzyansky factories built houses, cast cannons and bells, kept the Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestor, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then around stood wooden rooms for carriages, stables and guard booths, subsequently demolished.
In 1968, they wanted to clean our house, but something prevented us from doing so.
History repeated itself in 2014: again lured by new housing.
We, as a team, collected all the documents, bypassed the necessary authorities, and suddenly found out that the move to apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
I don’t believe in all this anymore...
Two years ago, Lavrentyev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
Officials did not accept the tenant.
They sent from one table to another, and then, as a mockery, they issued a piece of paper without a signature and seal: “The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of the tenants.”
I even got the feeling that our house is no longer in terms of the city, because at first it was number 57, then it became 57 A, and now it is 57/1.
It's like it was already demolished in the '70s.
"Russian planet" appealed to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the Department of land resources of Ufa Vladimir Barabash.
The house on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 is included in the program of settling dilapidated housing.
I can not be responsible for the actions of officials of the 70s, but I know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all old houses, despite the historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities to restore all the old houses along the street of the October Revolution, which are of architectural value, is being successfully implemented.
Residents will soon be resettled in new apartments.
According to Barabash, Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice will restore the Demidov House.
Now in Italy there is an architectural biennial, and the project "Old Ufa" is presented there among others.
I hope that by 2016 all the former Old Kazanskaya Street will be restored, the official said.
The houses will acquire the proper look, corresponding to the one that was before, three centuries ago.
The Demidov House is likely to become a museum open to all comers.
In addition, at the government level, it was decided to make the street pedestrian on weekends.
On weekdays, unfortunately, it will not work, too much traffic in the city.
Vladimir Barabash promises to settle people from the future museum in 2015.
However, they are unlikely to be satisfied: their new apartments will be the same area as the current ones.
Only from another era.
