Production in the Eurozone at the lowest level in 13 months
Eurozone production growth slowed to its lowest level in 13 months in August, according to a popular study.
The latest value of the business activity index (PMI) of the Eurozone manufacturing sector for Markit fell to 50.7 in August, down from 51.8 in July.
A value above 50 indicates growth.
New orders have been delayed and businesses have suffered amid growing tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The figures came ahead of a meeting of the European Central Bank (ECB) on Thursday.
Markets will be waiting for the bank to have a clear plan for how to deal with the eurozone’s recovery and the threat of deflation with inflation of just 0.3%.
There is speculation that ECB chief Mario Draghi could give additional signals later this week that he is mulling a quantitative easing scheme for the eurozone similar to those used by the UK and US during the financial crisis.
“While some growth is better than none at all, the drag on producers from growing economic and geopolitical uncertainty is becoming more apparent,” said Rob Dobson, Markit’s senior economist.
PMI of Germany’s manufacturing sector, Russia’s biggest trading partner in the EU, fell to its lowest level in 11 months at 51.4.
Meanwhile, in the bloc’s second-largest economy, France, PMI fell to 46.9.
France continues to be a real concern, as does Italy’s weakening from stable growth to stagnation.
“Indications that the growth momentum has waned mainly in the industrial engine, Germany, as well as in Spain and the Netherlands, also don’t add confidence,” Dobson said.
The slowdown in industry is likely to add fuel to analysts expecting additional monetary or fiscal stimulus.
One positive news was from Ireland, where PMI rose to 57.3, its highest level since late 1999.
Howard Archer, chief economist at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing to say about the August survey of the eurozone manufacturing sector’s business activity index is that it shows that the sector is still growing.”
He added: “Euro zone producers are obviously finding life very difficult at the moment, as the current increased geopolitical tensions — especially those related to Russia/Ukraine — add to the uncertainties of still challenging conditions in many countries.
This increased tension has obviously hit business - and especially consumer confidence, and likely leads to some orders being delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
