Just two weeks earlier, he had been skiing in the French Alps.
X-ray results came in.
It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or lining of the lungs.
For most cancers, it is difficult to determine the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients smoked.
But mesothelioma is different.
In almost all cases, the reason is contact with asbestos, a fibrous building material that was once called a “miracle,” but which is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be ignored.
Asbestos, after all, is a material from the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when a recommendatory industrial ban came into force.
Even when it was used, only people from specific industries worked closely with it: pipe-insulators, builders, carpenters, and dockworkers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it hardly seems a cause for concern today.
But that calm is wrong.
Britain, it turns out, is at the peak of the mesothelioma epidemic today.
More people die from mesothelioma here than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death toll of about 2,500, more than twice as many people die from the disease than from car accidents.
Annual number of deaths from mesothelioma since 1980 and projected number of future deaths in the UK
The reason we feel its deadly effects now is that although the use of asbestos has been illegal for many years (all types of asbestos were eventually banned by law in 1999), mesothelioma development usually takes decades.
And the attack of mesothelioma is not limited to veterans of industrial construction specialties.
Asbestos has been, and in many cases remains, embedded in the homes where we live, the offices where we work, the schools where we study, and the shops where we shop.
As a result, mesothelioma does not pay attention to class, wealth level, profession or age.
The bastions of choice, from fashionable London department stores to private schools, have proven to be no salvation.
The parliament building is riddled with asbestos.
Even hospitals that are designed to treat us have turned out to be reservoirs of this deadly carcinogen.
Andrew Lawson wasn't old.
He wasn't a pipe-insulator.
As a matter of fact, he had to think about where he could come into contact with asbestos.
Then he figured it out.
"It seems there could have been a lot of asbestos in the tunnels at Guy's Hospital, where I spent six years on an internship," he wrote.
All the students, nurses, doctors and loaders used these tunnels.
