It is expected that the document will be adopted in late September - early October, says Pluzhnikov, the proposed measures concern electric vehicles and hybrids - a plan for the development of vehicles on gas engine fuel in Russia already has.
The plan (a copy of Vedomosti) is designed for 2014-2017.
Criteria for the evaluation of electric and hybrid transport should be developed and how to stimulate the use and production of environmentally friendly vehicles.
The report to the government, which will describe tax and customs measures to support electric transport, will be prepared by December 2014; the scheme of concessional lending and preferential leasing will appear by April 2015; and proposals for reducing the price of cars, stimulating localization and creating a service infrastructure will be developed by October 2015.
In 2014-2015, it is planned to amend the regulatory acts to facilitate the conditions for the construction of charging infrastructure (at parking lots, gas stations, etc.).
In addition, federal officials intend to formulate proposals for regional authorities in 2015 that they also stimulate the use of environmentally friendly transport - in the form of providing it with an advantage when driving and parking, for example; and by February 2016 - and proposals to expand public procurement of such transport.
Finally, by October 2014, the Ministry of Economic Development will include in the list of indicators for assessing the activities of regional authorities criteria that reflect the effectiveness of supporting the production of environmentally friendly transport, the development of charging infrastructure.
The market of electric vehicles in Russia is still being formed - in 2013 about 100 electric vehicles were sold throughout the country.
At the beginning of 2014, the import duty on electric cars was zeroed, so sales will be about 500 units, predicts Andrey Pankov, chief executive officer of Mitsubishi Motors in Russia.
But a five-fold increase does not make electric cars any noticeable: in 2013, according to the Association of European Businesses, 2.78 million passenger cars and light commercial vehicles were sold in Russia.
So far, only Mitsubishi Motors has imported electric cars to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start imports - the company focuses primarily on corporate customers, says Nicolas Remiz, director of strategic planning and partnerships at Renault in Russia.
Most other manufacturers of electric transport took a wait-and-see attitude towards Russia.
Developments of electric vehicles have Russian manufacturers - "", GAZ, "", but the output is negligible.
For example, in January - July 2014, according to "ASM-holding", "AvtoVAZ" produced 30 electric vehicles.
Demand is low because of the high cost of electric vehicles, admits the Director of "AVTOVAZ" in engineering Sergey Amanov, without state support for a breakthrough in this segment will not.
The development of the Russian market of electric vehicles in addition to the high cost of cars (those electric cars sold in Russia, on average, twice as expensive as analogues with internal combustion engines) restrains the underdevelopment of the charging infrastructure (gas stations - units), sighs the General Director of "Autostat" Sergey Tselikov.
Due to the high cost and low rate of cost reduction, electric vehicles in the next 3-4 years will remain a niche segment of the Russian market, predicts the editor-in-chief of Avtorev Mikhail Podorozhansky, Tselikov agrees with him.
Automakers, by contrast, say that some models of electric vehicles are already close to the cost of conventional ones.
The Russian market of electric vehicles has good prospects, the main thing is to instill confidence in consumers that “electric mobility” is real; in particular, the emergence of new charging stations will contribute to this, says Wolfgang Schlimme, President of the BMW Group in Russia.
Such infrastructure projects are being implemented, for example, by the state-owned company Rosseti: several stations have been built in Moscow, and about 80 more will soon appear.
Negotiations on the construction of a network of gas stations are also underway with other regions.
According to the director of the Rosseti department, Vladimir Sofiin, the company believes in the electric vehicle market and is ready to build refueling stations throughout the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric vehicles in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric vehicles of various brands.
In addition, "Rosseti" as a grid company is not entitled to engage in the sale of electricity, the ability to do so in relation to charging electric vehicles.
Pankov considers the most effective measure of state support for the formation of the electric vehicle market in Russia to zero customs duties.
The zero rate will be valid until the end of 2014, the possibility of its extension, expansion of the preferential list is being considered.
Replacing the transport tax with an environmental one (the idea is discussed and concerns all cars) will also support the market, but not as much as customs preferences, Pankov believes.
Transport tax in Russia is small, says Pankov, unlike, for example, in Norway, where the tax cut led to a sharp increase in sales of electric vehicles - now they account for 12% of the market.
In Russia, incentives are also needed for car owners, for example, free parking in the city center (as has already been done in Moscow), Pankov is sure, or the possibility of moving electric vehicles along dedicated lanes, which is not yet possible in Russia.
