The program of car recycling resumed from September 1
From September 1, the program for car recycling is resumed in Russia.
Until December 31, 2014, 10 billion rubles will be allocated for these purposes.
As explained by the head of the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation Denis Manturov, the money is allocated from the limits that have already been brought to the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation by redistribution from other areas of support.
The program will cover all cars older than six years.
The amount of compensation will be from 40 thousand for a passenger car to 350 thousand rubles for a truck.
Earlier in Russia there was a similar program of car recycling.
The main difference of the current project, the minister explained, is that now it is expected not only to dispose of cars to obtain a subsequent discount, but also the opportunity, if the car has reached the age of more than six years, to purchase a new one at a discount when renting the old one to a "trade-in" from a dealer.
More than 16 billion rubles were spent on the previous federal recycling program, which was in effect from January 1, 2010 to December 31, 2011.
Thanks to it, the level of production of passenger cars in 2010 amounted to about 1.2 million units (this is plus 101.4% compared to 2009).
The creator of Coming Out Simulator will release a game about modern journalism
Game designer Nikki Case, known for the game Coming Out Simulator decided to release a game about modern journalism.
He spoke about his project in an interview with Kill Screen.
Case began work on the game a few weeks ago, but this fact is widely known only now.
The game was inspired by the Ferguson protests, which began after a police officer killed an unarmed black teenager.
The focus of the project, which does not yet have a name, will be how information coverage of stories affects their consequences.
The hero of the game, a citizen journalist, will need to photograph what is happening in areas where clashes between the police and the population occur.
The hero can take different photos of what is happening, which will affect the course of events.
If he shoots the scene in such a way that the police will look like heroes, and the protesters - bandits, the police will start to treat him better and let him go where an ordinary person can not go.
If he covers events differently, his photographs could turn peaceful protests into a massive riot.
Points in the game will need to be typed using the hero’s Twitter, in which new subscribers will appear if the photos posted there turn out to be popular.
The game has no title yet.
The release date and platforms on which it will appear are unknown.
Case, however, has published an image showing how an event can change depending on how a photo of it is taken and processed.
In an interview with Kill Screen, Case explained that he had been thinking about the concept of such a game for a long time, but initially wanted to devote it not to protests in the United States, but to events in the Gaza Strip.
After he started collecting material for the game, the game designer realized that he lacked the knowledge and skills to cover the history of the region.
However, when he saw how the media cover the events in Ferguson, he decided to make a game based on what happened.
Nikki Case is an independent developer who produces browser games.
His most famous project was Coming Out Simulator, released in 2014.
This game, which tells about the events from the biography of Case himself, is devoted to how a bisexual teenager tries to tell about his relationship to homophobic parents.
