The army controls the new government of Thailand
General Prayut (right) appointed Pravit Wongsuwan as Defence Minister (left)
Thailand's military ruler and prime minister, General Prayuth Chan-o-cha, has announced the composition of the country's new cabinet, in which more than a third of the posts are held by retired generals or generals.
Representatives of the army received key positions: ministers of defense, finance, foreign affairs and trade.
Prayuth Chan-o-cha was formally confirmed as prime minister on Monday after the Thai king formally approved the appointment of the head of the interim military government to the post.
The 60-year-old, who seized power in a bloodless coup on May 22, was the only candidate for the premiership.
He was elected Prime Minister at a meeting of Parliament.
The army has previously appointed members of parliament.
According to Prayut Chan-ocha, the coup was the only way to maintain stability.
It was preceded by six months of demonstrations, during which protesters demanded the resignation of the government of Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra.
Officially, Prayut Chan-o-cha will be interim prime minister as the military plans to hold a general election in late 2015.
However, there are fears that the military is trying to strengthen its power in the country.
The military came to power on May 22.
against the background of complete paralysis of civil power.
The leaders of the main political parties were temporarily arrested.
Immediately after the military came to power, they temporarily arrested leading politicians of the country, including Prime Minister Yinglik Shinawatra.
Some journalists and public figures were also detained.
The current political crisis dates back to 2006, when the army ousted Yinglik's brother Shinawath Thaksin as prime minister.
Both of them are popular among the rural population, especially in the northern regions of the country, which has repeatedly ensured their success in the elections.
However, many members of the middle class and the metropolitan elite entered the anti-government movement, which has practically paralyzed the country since November 2013.
