Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
The British woman said that she spent many years thinking that she would die, after a misdiagnosis.
Caryn Rogers spent much of her teenage years thinking she only had a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Toot disease (SMT), a group of hereditary disorders that lead to damage to nerves outside the brain and spine.
CMT UK has reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with SMT because so little is known about the condition.
About 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have SMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, uncertain gait, and squeezing toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and would die before she was 30.
A mother of two, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot in school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at the medical record when her doctor left the room and it was written there that she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where I shouldn’t, and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I came home, found information about this condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic possible.
I thought that I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that gap.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up and hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease because you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that's much less life threatening.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have SMT.
“When he explained what a SMT is, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK charity SMT has announced a month of information about SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
Tax burden on Washington area entrepreneurs rises as economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and more jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased moderately last year as the recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local coffers in fiscal 2013, a 3.8 percent increase from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on state and local businesses increased by 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after successive years when bills were down in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from taxes on entrepreneurs, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, generates the least tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
Largely, the increase in tax revenue is driven by a return to the previous level of the value of real estate companies, the researchers say, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row, when the growth was less than 1 percent.
While large states such as California, New York, and Texas account for a large share of these revenues, the same appears to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 — a 4.2 percent increase from the previous year.
However, the observed return in real estate value has no similar effect on state and local tax revenue growth in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies’ tax accounts.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned by either the government or a nonprofit that doesn’t pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center for State Taxation.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that are available in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Incomes of entrepreneurs also seem to be on the rise, according to these figures.
Companies in the region declared state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although the trends are directed in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level does not increase at the same rate in all three localities.
Growth in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average of 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, at 4.9 percent.
Virginia alone saw below-average tax revenue growth of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) at 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not assessed in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor from the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, the law could raise the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to even 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to feel better and thus pay more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners — the transitional structure under which most small firms are organized — in the District of Columbia, Maryland, and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
The researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind, as the decline in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
