Deputies proposed to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
In case of success of the initiative, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
The State Duma introduced a draft law providing for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed in the base of legislative activity of the lower house.
Its authors were State Duma deputies Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Fair Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to more rapid and effective ensuring the rights of Russian citizens to the safety of personal data and the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is rushed by the parliamentarians, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed through the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and extract personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as indicating the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of offending sites - an automated information system "Register of infringers of the rights of subjects of personal data".
This law was adopted by the state Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia will have to pay rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, First Deputy Head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own personal data stores of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation will be able to rent them, for example, from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies that today already provide their servers.
“In addition, there are several independent data centers willing to cooperate in this area,” he added.
“If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the territory of the Russian Federation, I do not see any problems - they will receive technological opportunities for placement,” Levin said.
The Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is adopted, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking of air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation."
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be the creation of a mechanism to inform the user about where the record is made, the systematization of his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose in which territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of such bills on the “localization” of personal data in other countries has led to the departure of global services and significant economic losses.
