Industry research shows that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores during the last spring semester were rented, says Nibo Vice President Trevor Meyer.
Less than half of all books are purchased from university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here is the introduction course on the best ways to make a profitable deal.
Buying in an online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book can be one-third of what you see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of Mathematical Analysis by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler costs about $290 on the price list, but a new copy can be purchased for $239.99 on Chegg.com, which specializes in selling textbooks.
Purchase of used
If you don’t mind someone else’s markings or damage, second-hand textbooks are a good option.
"Mathematical Analysis" sells for $93.49 at Chegg.com.
Matt Casadey, a 25-year-old fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a used copy of the textbook Strategic Decisions in Media: Understanding the Business Side of the Advertising Business.
The book sold for $48.
Teachers, such as Ingrid Bracey, director of the College Without Walls at the University of Massachusetts at Emherst, suggest that students ask their professors if they can use previous editions.
Sometimes updates are not important for classes.
In such cases, old editions can often be found for a very small fraction of the cost of the latest edition.
Apart from Chegg and Amazon, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative for buying used books.
Rent
It is worth thinking about renting textbooks, if you treat them well enough, do not forget to return them and do not want to keep them after the course is over.
You can save more than 80% on the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent a "Mathematical Analysis" for a semester for about $20.
Find out the rules of the store where you take the books, including any fines that you may be issued for markings, underscores and damage.
If you rent a book, remember: if you do not return the book, the fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually rented by purchasing an electronic license for a certain period from distributors, for example, Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes & Noble Inc.
Renting a "Mathematical Analysis" on Chegg.com for six months will cost about $ 61.
Bracey says that students of literature can often find the most favorable prices, since many classical works can now be downloaded for free, while literature in the natural and engineering sciences can be quite expensive.
No matter what, look around.
Joe Gault, 29, who is about to start his studies at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using the ISBN number to find out the prices of the book, as this ensures that you are looking for the right text for you.
Before ordering online, Holt says, be sure to check if the book is actually in stock.
This lesson was not easy for him.
The delivery of the book he purchased was delayed by four weeks, and he eventually paid the full price at the university bookstore.
