Why “Guardians of the Galaxy” Couldn’t Save the Box Office
Sylvester Stallone’s “The Expendables 3” returned less than $30 million from its $90 million budget in the US, while Sin City: A Woman Worth Killing for returned only $12 million from its $70 million budget.
Cameron Diaz’s “home video” only grossed $14.6 million in its opening weekend, while children’s films like How to Train Your Dragon 2 also disappoint with revenue.
An article by Telegraph film critic Robbie Collin points out that when it comes to children's films, perhaps it's the poor quality of the films themselves.
Collin called 2014 the "worst" year ever for children's films, and called How to Train Your Dragon 2 a barely "functioning" fantasy sequel.
However, when it comes to films aimed at an older audience, it seems that the problem does not necessarily lie in the quality of the films themselves.
In July, Entertainment Weekly compared the average CinemaScore and Metacritic ratings of each film released in the summer in the amount of at least 2,000 copies between the Memorial Day holiday of May and July 20, for 2013 and for this year.
The results, which take into account the opinion of both film viewers and film critics, suggest that the harvest of this year’s films is similar in caliber to last year’s hits.
Some commentators suggest that the case may be in the changing viewing habits and growing popularity of streaming Internet services such as Netflix.
Director John Favreau, who is currently working on the soon-to-be-released Disney movie The Jungle Book, told the Hollywood Reporter website: "I think times are changing."
We must acknowledge this and not try to chase after what came before.
In contrast to the current drop in the box office in Hollywood, Netflix’s revenue from the streaming service reached $ 1.2 billion, almost double last year’s figure of $ 837 million.
Last summer, director Steven Spielberg criticized the studios for relying too much on comic book franchises, and predicted the “collapse” of Hollywood.
In light of the current downturn, some commentators argue that there was some truth to his dire predictions.
Due to the fact that in the summer of 2015 several potential box office hits are expected, including “Avengers: Age of Ultron”, “Minions” and “Yursky Park”, other representatives of the film industry are more optimistic.
"X-Men" producer Simon Kinberg recently called the fall in box office revenue simply "cyclical," telling the Hollywood Reporter: "Next summer will be the highest-grossing summer in history, and no one will worry about it."
