"Europrotocol" instead of a certificate of traffic police
Cash payments can be received without a certificate from the traffic police - so the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the "Europrotocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft guidelines, according to which from September 1 of this year, an insured motorist will be able to do without a certificate from the traffic police.
We are talking, however, only about those cases when the accident was registered on the “Euro Protocol” without the participation of the traffic police.
That is, if only two cars participated in the accident, there are no physically injured persons, the damage does not exceed the established limit and both drivers reached an agreement on who was responsible for the accident.
From August 2, the limit of payments for the "Europrotocol" is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in the Moscow and Leningrad regions, it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The bottom line is that often even with minor damage, in a situation where an accident can be registered on the "Europrotocol", drivers who have been involved in an accident call the traffic police.
After all, in the presence of a casco policy, it was impossible to receive compensation for it without a certificate from the traffic police.
The parameters prescribed in the draft guidance are designed to eliminate this obstacle to the introduction of the “Europrotocol” in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payment on insurance in connection with an accident, issued without traffic police officers, should not be lower than the limit on the "Europrotocol".
But at the same time, it can not be higher than the limit specified in the Casco insurance contract.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically able to unload both employees of the traffic police and roads.
But, most likely, neither motorists nor insurers will be delighted with it.
The latter are already talking about a serious threat to the growth of fraud, which can lead to the introduction of new rules for payment of cash.
As for drivers, it is difficult to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome the traditional Russian conservatism.
In most cases, the driver will wait for hours for the inspector to arrange a minor accident, because this is more reliable.
And yet it is not known what will be easier - to defeat fraudsters or convince drivers of the reliability of the "Europrotocol".
Savings certificate will be named and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates for bearer, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of an irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will prohibit savings certificates for bearer.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, since the rates here are higher than for bank deposits.
The fact is that bearer savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since it is not necessary to make contributions to the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA) fund.
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken due to small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to ASV, control 98% of the profile market, will suffer from it.
Moreover, the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the Agency’s estimates, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the DIA, is that the customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his license, try to get money in the DIA.
Some investors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying bearer savings certificates, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments for these certificates in case of revocation of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court,” the DIA said.
The problem is, of course, far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, since they do not have the right to compensation from the state by law.
If it were the case that the instrument is not insured in the DIA, along with it would prohibit metal accounts, in which citizens' funds are counted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one has yet attempted to exist.
The fact, most likely, is that bearer certificates are a very convenient security, which can actually act as quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is practically beyond control: any bank client can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing out, such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must be a personal security, which must be stored in a depository.
And to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of the irrevocable contribution, which bankers have long dreamed of, is introduced.
