Frank Miller and Robert Rodriguez’s “Sin City 2: A Woman Worth Killing For” revolutionized everything you’d expect.
The first “Sin City” (2005), shot with the minimal but symbolic participation of Quentin Tarantino, revolutionized the relationship between cinema, comics and literary noir.
The sequel is also revolutionary in its own way: in the sense that it destroys the chain of “thesis-antithesis-synthesis” (if we mean the noir universe by the thesis, and the comics space by the antithesis) that is fundamental to modern thinking.
From now on, it should read: "thesis - antithesis - chaos."
Sin City 2 is chaotic both on a dramatic and philosophical level: both times it is chaotic in the bad sense of the word.
Yes, some of the heroes are familiar from the first "City", although, here, rumbled Marv (Mickey Rourke), I remember, ended his life in an electric chair, and here, nothing, only manages to snatch - in the role of a folk vigilante - knives and other axes with chokes.
