Putin granted Russian citizenship to the Ukrainian pentathlon
Russian President Vladimir Putin has granted Russian citizenship to the famous Ukrainian athlete Anna Buryak.
The relevant decree was published on the Internet portal of legal information.
Earlier this year, the athlete moved to Russia for permanent residence and appealed to the Federation of modern pentathlon with a request to give her the opportunity to play for the national team of the Russian Federation.
In 2013, she won two stages of the World Cup, won the silver medal of the European Championship in the personal championship and became the world champion in the mixed relay, which is one of the new types of program in this sport.
She still holds the leading position this season.
According to the rules, to compete at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, she will need to obtain a special permit from the Olympic Committee of Ukraine.
Anna Buryak is not the first Ukrainian athlete to change her citizenship.
In July, Vladimir Putin decided to issue a Russian passport to chess player Ekaterina Lagno, a native of Lviv, who is a two-time champion of Europe (2005, 2008), the world in blitz (2010) and fast chess (2014).
As part of the women's team of Ukraine, the athlete became the winner of the chess Olympiad in Turin (2006), the World Team Championship in Astana (2013) and the European Team Championship in Warsaw (2013).
TFR stopped the investigation of the crash of Tu-204 in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (TFR) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the aircraft commander and flight engineer.
Forensic examination showed that the cause of the crash was the increased speed of approach to the landing, the failure of the crew to comply with standard procedures for landing, as well as the unintended output of engines on increased speeds of direct thrust.
The plane Tu-204 airline Red Wings, following the flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft rolled out of the runway and caught fire.
At the scene killed the commander of the aircraft, co-pilot and flight engineer.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical institutions, where they later died from their injuries.
Three other flight attendants hospitalized with serious injuries underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car moving at the time of the crash on the Kiev highway received serious injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport Prosecutor’s office after the disaster conducted in the Red Wings inspection, during which numerous violations were revealed.
In February 2013, the airline's license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
