Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of a person
Angry facial expression is biologically universal for mankind, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the United States found.
They described their findings in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release from the University of California at Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - shifted and lowered eyebrows, elongated lips in a thin line, swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and even blind children from birth who have never seen it, notes the study's lead author Aaron Sell.
As part of a large research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion arose to effectively conduct disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can cause to another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his conditions, and he conveys this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmation of their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and turn to violence, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and also prefer forceful methods of resolving conflicts peacefully.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining”, scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry expression of the face should represent an angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thereby force him to agree to his conditions as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated a face on a computer where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or absent, and showed them to the informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or forward chin separately did not make the face evil, the person depicted with such traits is physically stronger, the study participants unanimously recognized.
The anger of man, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one's own power, forcing one to agree and obey.
A person inflates their nostrils and presses their lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that shows off its fangs.
Anger is “launched” by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that most effectively demonstrates the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tobey.
The Ministry of communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV and radio company “Crimea”
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget to the autonomous non-profit organization “Crimea TV and Radio Company” in 2014.
This is stated in the draft government resolution prepared by the agency, which was reviewed by Lenta.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed “to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment.”
In particular, it is planned to convert the hardware and studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server with the allocated money.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication lines (FOX) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget funds provided for the Ministry of Communications.
State broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959, broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the TV and radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, the TV and Radio Company "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
